    "summary": "Humayun (r. 1530–1540, 1555–1556 AD) was the second [[event:103|Mughal Emperor]] — a ruler of genuine talent but chronically unlucky, who lost the empire his father [[event:2512|Babur]] had founded to the Afghan chieftain [[event:3234|Sher Shah Suri]], spent 15 years in exile across Persia and Afghanistan, and finally recovered his throne only to die accidentally six months later. Humayun's first reign was undone by a combination of his own indecision, his alienation of capable brothers whom he failed to reward, and the military genius of Sher Shah Suri, who defeated him twice (at Chausa in 1539 and at Kannauj in 1540). His exile to the Safavid Persian court was also his cultural education: the Persian artistic traditions he absorbed and the Persian artists he brought back transformed Mughal court culture, laying foundations for the distinctive Indo-Persian style of [[event:2381|Akbar's]] great court.\n\nHumayun's 15-year exile was also the period in which his son Akbar was born (in Umarkot, Sindh, in 1542), under circumstances of such poverty and uncertainty that the birth was celebrated with the sharing of a single pod of musk among companions. With Safavid military support, Humayun reconquered Kabul (1545) and then Delhi (1555), restoring the Mughal dynasty — only to die in January 1556 when he fell down the stone stairs of his library after hearing the call to prayer, slipping on his robe while hurrying to descend. He left the empire to 13-year-old Akbar, under the regency of Bairam Khan, who would stabilize and transform the Mughal state into one of history's great empires.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humayun",
